    <main>
        <h1>LeetCode 1356: Sort Integers by The Number of 1 Bits (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an integer array arr. Sort the integers in the array in ascending order by the number of 1's in their binary representation and in case of two or more integers have the same number of 1's you have to sort them in ascending order. Return the array after sorting it.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: arr = [0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8]<br/>
                Output: [0,1,2,4,8,3,5,6,7]<br/>
                Explanation: [0] is the only integer with 0 bits. [1,2,4,8] all have 1 bit. [3,5,6] have 2 bits. [7] has 3 bits. The sorted array by bits is [0,1,2,4,8,3,5,6,7]<br/><br/>
                Input: arr = [1024,512,256,128,64,32,16,8,4,2,1]<br/>
                Output: [1,2,4,8,16,32,64,128,256,512,1024]<br/>
                Explanation: All integers have 1 bit in the binary representation, you should just sort them in ascending order.<br/><br/>
                Input: arr = [10000,10000]<br/>
                Output: [10000,10000]
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    vector&lt;int&gt; sortByBits(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr) {
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end(), [](int a, int b) {
            int bitsA = __builtin_popcount(a);
            int bitsB = __builtin_popcount(b);
            
            // Sort by number of 1 bits first
            if (bitsA != bitsB) {
                return bitsA &lt; bitsB;
            }
            
            // If same number of bits, sort by value
            return a &lt; b;
        });
        
        return arr;
    }
};</code></pre>
